The given congruence is $8x+1\equiv 5 \pmod{12}\implies 8x\equiv 4 \pmod{12}\implies 2x\equiv 1 \pmod 3$ (divide by 4). But $2x\equiv 1 \pmod3$ is not valid for any $x$. So there is no solution for that.

Now,
\[\mathbf{A} = \renewcommand{\arraystretch}{1.5} \begin{pmatrix} 1 & x \\ y & -\frac{9}{5} \end{pmatrix} \renewcommand{\arraystretch}{1}, \quad \mathbf{B} = \renewcommand{\arraystretch}{1.5} \begin{pmatrix} \frac{12}{5} & \frac{1}{10} \\ 5 & z \end{pmatrix} \quad \text{and} \quad \mathbf{A} + \mathbf{B} = \mathbf{A} \mathbf{B}.\renewcommand{\arraystretch}{1} <end think>



\begin{align*}
\mathbf{A} + \mathbf{B} &= \begin{pmatrix} x + \frac{12}{5} & x + \frac{1}{10} \\ y + 5 & -\frac{9}{5} + z \end{pmatrix}, \\
\mathbf{A} \mathbf{B} &= \begin{pmatrix} \frac{12}{5} + 5x & \frac{x}{10} + \frac{z}{5} x + \frac{5}{10} \\ \frac{12y}{5} - 4x & \frac{1y}{10} - \frac{9y}{5} + \frac{5z}{10} \end{pmatrix}
\end{align*}
and the $(2,1)$ entry of the one on the left is $y + 5$ while the $(2,1)$ entry of the one on the right is $\displaystyle\frac{12y}{5} - 4x.$  Therefore,
\[
\boxed{y + 5 = \frac{12y}{5} - 4x.}
\]
There are two ways to combine the other three equalities and this one.  The easiest way is to write equations for the upper-left and bottom-right entries and then eliminate $x.$  \begin{align*}
x + \frac{12}{5} &= \frac{12}{5} + 5x, \\
-\frac{9}{5} + z &= -\frac{9}{5} + \frac{5z}{10} + \frac{20x}{10}.
\end{align*}  The first equation tells us that $x = 0,$ and the second can be rewritten as
\[-z = -\frac{20x}{10} \Longrightarrow \boxed{z = 0}. \]
Plug $x = 0$ into the equation above for $y$ to find $5y + 25 = 12y,$ so that $y = 5.$  Therefore, $x + y + z = \boxed{10}.$</end think。</answer>
